                <div class="lesson-content">
                    <h3 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-4">CHAPTER 5: IDENTIFYING TASK REQUIREMENTS</h3>

                    <p class="lead">Planning is essential for safe forklift operation. Before you start any work, you must clearly understand what tasks need to be performed. This chapter explains how to identify task requirements from various workplace sources.</p>

                    <div class="chapter-section mt-4">
                        <h4 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-3">Why Task Identification Matters</h4>

                        <p>Starting work without clearly understanding your tasks can lead to:</p>

                        <div class="task-risks-grid mt-3">
                            <div class="task-risk-item">üì¶ Loads being moved to wrong locations</div>
                            <div class="task-risk-item">üîç Time wasted searching for information</div>
                            <div class="task-risk-item">‚è±Ô∏è Delays in completing work</div>
                            <div class="task-risk-item">‚ö†Ô∏è Safety risks from incomplete planning</div>
                            <div class="task-risk-item">üîß Equipment or resources being unavailable when needed</div>
                            <div class="task-risk-item">‚ùì Confusion among team members</div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="alert alert-success mt-3">
                            <strong>Proper task identification ensures</strong> you know exactly what needs to be done, where, when, and how.
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="chapter-section mt-5">
                        <h4 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-3">Sources of Task Requirements</h4>

                        <p>In the workplace, task requirements come from several documented sources. You should check multiple sources to get complete information:</p>

                        <div class="task-sources-section mt-4">
                            <div class="task-source-card">
                                <div class="task-source-header">
                                    <div class="task-source-number">1</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Work Orders</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="task-source-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">A work order is a written instruction that details specific work to be performed. Work orders typically include:</p>
                                    <ul class="task-source-list">
                                        <li>Description of the task</li>
                                        <li>Loads to be moved (quantity, type, weight)</li>
                                        <li>Pick-up and delivery locations</li>
                                        <li>Time requirements or deadlines</li>
                                        <li>Special handling instructions</li>
                                        <li>Safety requirements</li>
                                        <li>Equipment needed</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="small mb-2">Work orders may be printed documents or digital records in a computer system. Always read work orders carefully from start to finish before beginning work.</p>
                                    <div class="task-example-box">
                                        <strong>Example:</strong> "Work Order #2847: Move 40 pallets of packaged goods from Loading Dock 3 to Warehouse Storage Bay B12. Completion required by 3:00 PM. Use standard forks. Maximum pallet weight: 800kg."
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="task-source-card">
                                <div class="task-source-header">
                                    <div class="task-source-number">2</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Job Cards</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="task-source-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Job cards are similar to work orders but may contain more specific technical information. They often include:</p>
                                    <ul class="task-source-list">
                                        <li>Detailed task steps</li>
                                        <li>Safety procedures</li>
                                        <li>Quality requirements</li>
                                        <li>Completion criteria</li>
                                        <li>Sign-off sections</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="small mb-0">Job cards may be used for routine tasks that are performed regularly.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="task-source-card">
                                <div class="task-source-header">
                                    <div class="task-source-number">3</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Supervisor Instructions</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="task-source-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Your supervisor or team leader provides verbal or written instructions about work to be performed. Supervisor instructions might include:</p>
                                    <ul class="task-source-list">
                                        <li>Priorities for the day</li>
                                        <li>Changes to normal procedures</li>
                                        <li>Coordination with other workers</li>
                                        <li>Safety concerns specific to current conditions</li>
                                        <li>Resource allocation</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="alert alert-warning mt-2 mb-2">
                                        <strong>Important:</strong> Always confirm your understanding of supervisor instructions. Repeat back what you heard to ensure you understood correctly.
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="task-dialogue-box">
                                        <div class="dialogue-line"><span class="dialogue-speaker supervisor">Supervisor:</span> "Move the cartons from bay 5 to the loading dock."</div>
                                        <div class="dialogue-line"><span class="dialogue-speaker operator">You:</span> "Just to confirm, I'm moving all cartons from bay 5 to loading dock 2, correct?"</div>
                                        <div class="dialogue-line"><span class="dialogue-speaker supervisor">Supervisor:</span> "Yes, that's right."</div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="task-source-card">
                                <div class="task-source-header">
                                    <div class="task-source-number">4</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Site Plans</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="task-source-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Site plans are drawings or maps showing:</p>
                                    <ul class="task-source-list">
                                        <li>Layout of the work area</li>
                                        <li>Location of storage bays or zones</li>
                                        <li>Loading and unloading areas</li>
                                        <li>Travel routes</li>
                                        <li>Hazard locations (powerlines, underground services)</li>
                                        <li>Restricted areas</li>
                                        <li>Emergency equipment locations</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="small mb-0">Site plans help you visualize where you need to go and plan your routes.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="task-source-card">
                                <div class="task-source-header">
                                    <div class="task-source-number">5</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Job Specifications</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="task-source-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Job specifications provide detailed technical requirements:</p>
                                    <ul class="task-source-list">
                                        <li>Load weights and dimensions</li>
                                        <li>Stacking heights or patterns</li>
                                        <li>Handling methods</li>
                                        <li>Storage requirements (temperature, orientation)</li>
                                        <li>Quality standards</li>
                                        <li>Documentation needed</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="small mb-0">Job specifications are particularly important for specialized or unusual loads.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="task-source-card">
                                <div class="task-source-header">
                                    <div class="task-source-number">6</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Delivery Dockets</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="task-source-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Delivery dockets accompany loads being delivered or dispatched. They show:</p>
                                    <ul class="task-source-list">
                                        <li>What is being moved</li>
                                        <li>Quantity of items</li>
                                        <li>Weight information</li>
                                        <li>Sender and receiver details</li>
                                        <li>Handling instructions ("This Way Up", "Fragile", etc.)</li>
                                        <li>Any special requirements</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="small mb-0">Always check delivery dockets against physical loads to ensure they match.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="task-source-card">
                                <div class="task-source-header">
                                    <div class="task-source-number">7</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Workplace Procedures</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="task-source-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Your workplace has standard operating procedures (SOPs) that describe how specific tasks should be performed. These procedures outline:</p>
                                    <ul class="task-source-list">
                                        <li>Step-by-step processes</li>
                                        <li>Safety requirements</li>
                                        <li>Equipment to use</li>
                                        <li>Documentation to complete</li>
                                        <li>Who to report to</li>
                                        <li>Emergency procedures</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="small mb-0">Workplace procedures ensure consistency and safety across all operations.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="chapter-section mt-5">
                        <h4 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-3">Process for Identifying Task Requirements</h4>

