                    <h3 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-4 mt-5">CHAPTER 6: ASSESSING THE WORK AREA</h3>

                    <p class="lead">Before operating a forklift in any work area, you must assess the operating surface to determine if it's suitable. An unsuitable surface is one of the leading causes of forklift tip-overs and accidents.</p>

                    <div class="chapter-section mt-4">
                        <h4 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-3">What is Surface Assessment?</h4>

                        <div class="alert alert-info">
                            <p class="mb-0"><strong>Surface assessment</strong> means checking the ground or floor where you'll be driving the forklift to ensure it can safely support the forklift and load. Not all surfaces are suitable for forklift operations.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="chapter-section mt-5">
                        <h4 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-3">Critical Factors to Assess</h4>

                        <div class="surface-factors-section mt-4">
                            <div class="surface-factor-card">
                                <div class="surface-factor-header">
                                    <div class="surface-factor-number">1</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Surface Condition (Firmness and Stability)</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="surface-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">The surface must be firm and stable enough to support the combined weight of:</p>
                                    <ul class="factor-list mb-3">
                                        <li>The forklift itself</li>
                                        <li>The maximum load you'll be carrying</li>
                                        <li>Dynamic forces from movement, turning, and braking</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="mb-2"><strong>Check for:</strong></p>
                                    <ul class="factor-list mb-3">
                                        <li>Solid concrete or asphalt (ideal surfaces)</li>
                                        <li>Compacted gravel or crushed rock (generally acceptable if well-maintained)</li>
                                        <li>Soft dirt, mud, or sand (unsuitable - forklift will sink)</li>
                                        <li>Areas that may have been undermined or weakened</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="factor-tip-box">
                                        <strong>How to test:</strong> Walk on the surface. If it feels soft, spongy, or unstable under your weight, it won't support a loaded forklift. Look for signs of previous surface failure like cracks, depressions, or areas where vehicles have sunk in.
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="surface-factor-card">
                                <div class="surface-factor-header">
                                    <div class="surface-factor-number">2</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Gradient and Slope</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="surface-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">The steepness or angle of the surface affects forklift stability. You must check:</p>
                                    <ul class="factor-list mb-3">
                                        <li>The degree of slope - Refer to your forklift's operator manual for maximum safe gradient. Typical limits are 10-15 degrees for most forklifts, but this varies by model.</li>
                                        <li>Whether you'll travel up or down slopes with a load - Different capacities may apply for uphill vs downhill operation.</li>
                                        <li>Cross-slopes (sideways angles) - These are particularly dangerous as they can cause sideways tipping.</li>
                                        <li>Changes in gradient along your path - Transitioning from flat to sloped surfaces requires extra caution.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="alert alert-danger">
                                        <strong>‚ö†Ô∏è Warning:</strong> Never turn on a slope. Always travel straight up or down. Turning on a slope dramatically increases the risk of tipping over.
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="surface-factor-card">
                                <div class="surface-factor-header">
                                    <div class="surface-factor-number">3</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Surface Material Type</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="surface-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Different surface materials provide different levels of grip and stability:</p>
                                    <ul class="factor-list mb-3">
                                        <li>Concrete - Excellent grip when dry, can be very slippery when wet or contaminated with oil</li>
                                        <li>Asphalt - Good grip, but can become soft in very hot weather</li>
                                        <li>Gravel - Acceptable if compacted, but loose gravel can shift under load</li>
                                        <li>Steel plates - Very slippery, especially when wet, oily, or cold</li>
                                        <li>Painted surfaces - Can be slippery, especially when wet</li>
                                        <li>Grass or dirt - Generally unsuitable unless specifically prepared and compacted</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="factor-tip-box">
                                        <strong>Consider weather effects:</strong> Rain, ice, or snow dramatically changes surface characteristics.
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="surface-factor-card">
                                <div class="surface-factor-header">
                                    <div class="surface-factor-number">4</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Load Bearing Capacity</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="surface-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">The surface must support the total weight without breaking, cracking, or deforming.</p>
                                    <p class="mb-2"><strong>Consider:</strong></p>
                                    <ul class="factor-list mb-3">
                                        <li>Total weight = Forklift weight + Maximum load + Dynamic forces</li>
                                        <li>Whether the surface is rated for heavy vehicles</li>
                                        <li>Signs of previous surface failure (cracks, settled areas, pot holes)</li>
                                        <li>Elevated surfaces like mezzanine floors or ramps - always check posted weight limits</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="factor-example-box">
                                        <strong>Example:</strong> A forklift weighs 3,000 kg. Maximum load is 2,500 kg. Total weight is 5,500 kg. The surface must safely support this, plus additional forces from movement.
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="surface-factor-card">
                                <div class="surface-factor-header">
                                    <div class="surface-factor-number">5</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Presence of Potholes or Uneven Areas</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="surface-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Uneven surfaces create serious hazards:</p>
                                    <ul class="factor-list mb-3">
                                        <li>Potholes can cause sudden jolts that dislodge loads</li>
                                        <li>Raised areas or speed bumps affect stability</li>
                                        <li>Uneven surfaces cause the forklift to tilt</li>
                                        <li>Edges of concrete slabs may break away under weight</li>
                                        <li>Sunken areas may indicate underground problems</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="mb-0">Even small potholes (50-100mm) can cause problems when traveling with a raised load.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="surface-factor-card">
                                <div class="surface-factor-header">
                                    <div class="surface-factor-number">6</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Wet or Slippery Conditions</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="surface-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Moisture and contamination reduce traction and increase risks:</p>
                                    <p class="mb-2"><strong>Check for:</strong></p>
                                    <ul class="factor-list mb-3">
                                        <li>Rain, water puddles, or melting ice</li>
                                        <li>Oil, grease, or hydraulic fluid spills</li>
                                        <li>Product spillage (liquids, powders)</li>
                                        <li>Morning dew or frost</li>
                                        <li>Recent cleaning activities (wet floors)</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="alert alert-warning">
                                        <strong>Warning:</strong> A surface that's safe when dry may become dangerous when wet. Always reassess after weather changes.
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="surface-factor-card">
                                <div class="surface-factor-header">
                                    <div class="surface-factor-number">7</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Presence of Debris or Obstacles</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="surface-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Objects on the surface create hazards:</p>
                                    <ul class="factor-list mb-3">
                                        <li>Loose materials (wood scraps, metal, packaging)</li>
                                        <li>Dropped products or broken pallets</li>
                                        <li>Hoses, cables, or chains across travel paths</li>
                                        <li>Tools or equipment left in traffic areas</li>
                                        <li>Waste, wrapping materials, or packaging</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="mb-0">Even small objects under a tyre can cause instability.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="chapter-section mt-5">
                        <h4 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-3">Surface Assessment Procedure</h4>

                        <p>Follow these steps for every new work area:</p>

                        <div class="assessment-steps-container mt-4">
                            <div class="assessment-step">
                                <div class="assessment-step-number">1</div>
                                <div class="assessment-step-content">
                                    <h6 class="fw-bold">Visual Inspection</h6>
                                    <p class="mb-0">Walk through the entire work area and visually inspect all surfaces where you'll operate. Look for obvious hazards and unsuitable conditions.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="assessment-step">
                                <div class="assessment-step-number">2</div>
                                <div class="assessment-step-content">
                                    <h6 class="fw-bold">Physical Testing</h6>
                                    <p class="mb-0">Where appropriate, test surface firmness by walking on it. Push on suspect areas with your foot. If the surface feels unstable to walk on, it won't support a loaded forklift.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="assessment-step">
                                <div class="assessment-step-number">3</div>
                                <div class="assessment-step-content">
                                    <h6 class="fw-bold">Check Documentation</h6>
                                    <p class="mb-0">Review site plans or posted load ratings. Check if there are restrictions on vehicle weights in certain areas.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="assessment-step">
                                <div class="assessment-step-number">4</div>
                                <div class="assessment-step-content">
                                    <h6 class="fw-bold">Consider Weather</h6>
                                    <p class="mb-0">Think about recent and current weather. Has it been raining? Is there frost? How will this affect surfaces?</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="assessment-step">
                                <div class="assessment-step-number">5</div>
                                <div class="assessment-step-content">
                                    <h6 class="fw-bold">Consult Others</h6>
                                    <p class="mb-0">Ask site personnel about any known surface issues or areas to avoid. Maintenance staff or other operators may know about problems.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="assessment-step">
                                <div class="assessment-step-number">6</div>
                                <div class="assessment-step-content">
                                    <h6 class="fw-bold">Record Findings</h6>
                                    <p class="mb-0">Document any surface issues or concerns. Take photos if needed. Report unsuitable surfaces to your supervisor.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="chapter-section mt-5">
                        <h4 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-3">When Surfaces Are Unsuitable</h4>

                        <div class="alert alert-danger">
                            <h6 class="fw-bold">If you determine a surface is unsuitable, you MUST:</h6>
                            <ul class="mb-0">
                                <li>Not operate the forklift on that surface</li>
                                <li>Report the issue to your supervisor immediately</li>
                                <li>Document what you found</li>
                                <li>Suggest alternative routes if available</li>
                                <li>Wait for the surface to be repaired or improved</li>
                                <li>Never compromise safety to meet deadlines</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="chapter-section mt-5">
                        <h4 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-3">Key Points to Remember</h4>

                        <div class="key-points-grid">
                            <div class="key-point-item">‚úì Assess every new work area before operating</div>
                            <div class="key-point-item">‚úì Check all seven critical factors</div>
                            <div class="key-point-item">‚úì Test surface firmness physically</div>
                            <div class="key-point-item">‚úì Consider weather effects</div>
                            <div class="key-point-item">‚úì Document and report unsuitable surfaces</div>
                            <div class="key-point-item">‚úì Never operate on surfaces you've assessed as unsuitable</div>
                            <div class="key-point-item">‚úì Continue monitoring throughout your shift</div>
                            <div class="key-point-item">‚úì When in doubt, ask for help</div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="key-message-box mt-4">
                            <div class="key-message-icon">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
                            <div class="key-message-content">
                                <p class="mb-0">Surface assessment is not just a checklist item - it's a critical safety practice that prevents tip-overs and injuries.</p>
                            </div>
