                    <h3 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-4 mt-5">CHAPTER 7: PLANNING SAFE TRAVEL PATHS</h3>

                    <p class="lead">A travel path is the route you'll take when moving the forklift from one location to another. Planning appropriate travel paths before you start the engine is essential for safe operations.</p>

                    <div class="chapter-section mt-4">
                        <h4 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-3">Why Path Planning Matters</h4>

                        <div class="row">
                            <div class="col-md-6">
                                <div class="path-planning-box path-planning-bad">
                                    <h6 class="fw-bold mb-3">‚ùå Poor path planning leads to:</h6>
                                    <ul class="mb-0">
                                        <li>Collisions with people, structures, or other vehicles</li>
                                        <li>Getting stuck in areas with inadequate clearance</li>
                                        <li>Delays from having to reverse and find alternative routes</li>
                                        <li>Damage to loads, equipment, or buildings</li>
                                        <li>Safety incidents that could have been prevented</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="col-md-6">
                                <div class="path-planning-box path-planning-good">
                                    <h6 class="fw-bold mb-3">‚úì Good path planning ensures:</h6>
                                    <ul class="mb-0">
                                        <li>You choose the safest and most efficient route</li>
                                        <li>Adequate clearances throughout the journey</li>
                                        <li>Minimal conflicts with other traffic</li>
                                        <li>Proper preparation for challenging sections</li>
                                        <li>Professional, efficient operations</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="chapter-section mt-5">
                        <h4 class="text-primary fw-bold mb-3">Nine Critical Assessment Factors</h4>

                        <div class="path-factors-section mt-4">
                            <div class="path-factor-card">
                                <div class="path-factor-header">
                                    <div class="path-factor-number">1</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Width of Pathways and Aisles</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="path-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">You must ensure pathways are wide enough for:</p>
                                    <ul class="mb-3">
                                        <li>The forklift body width</li>
                                        <li>The load width (which may be wider than the forklift)</li>
                                        <li>Safe clearance on both sides (minimum 600mm recommended total)</li>
                                        <li>Passing other vehicles or pedestrians if needed</li>
                                        <li>Some margin for steering error</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="path-calculation-box mb-3">
                                        <strong>Measure or calculate total width needed:</strong>
                                        <p class="formula-text mb-0">Forklift width + Load overhang (if any) + Clearance = Minimum pathway width</p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="path-example-box">
                                        <strong>Example:</strong> Forklift is 1.2m wide, load is 1.5m wide (extends 150mm each side), need 300mm each side clearance = minimum pathway width of <strong>2.1m</strong>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3 mb-0">
                                        <strong>‚ö†Ô∏è Warning:</strong> Narrow aisles restrict your ability to maneuver and increase collision risks.
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="path-factor-card">
                                <div class="path-factor-header">
                                    <div class="path-factor-number">2</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Height Clearances</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="path-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Check all overhead clearances along your route:</p>
                                    <ul class="mb-3">
                                        <li>Doorways and door frames</li>
                                        <li>Overhead beams, pipes, or ductwork</li>
                                        <li>Lighting fixtures and signs</li>
                                        <li>Cable trays and conduit</li>
                                        <li>Low ceilings in certain areas</li>
                                        <li>Overhead storage racks</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="path-calculation-box mb-3">
                                        <strong>Critical: Height clearance needed =</strong>
                                        <p class="formula-text mb-0">Forklift mast height + Load height + Safety margin (typically 300mm)</p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="path-tip-box">
                                        <strong>Don't forget:</strong>
                                        <ul class="mb-0">
                                            <li>Your load height when elevated</li>
                                            <li>Mast height varies depending on tilt angle</li>
                                            <li>Some structures may have variable heights</li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="mt-3 mb-0"><strong>Always check height clearances with the load at maximum anticipated height.</strong></p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="path-factor-card">
                                <div class="path-factor-header">
                                    <div class="path-factor-number">3</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Surface Conditions Along the Route</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="path-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Your entire travel path must have suitable surfaces (as covered in Chapter 6):</p>
                                    <ul class="mb-3">
                                        <li>Check for changes in surface type (concrete to gravel)</li>
                                        <li>Identify transitions between surfaces</li>
                                        <li>Note any slopes or gradients</li>
                                        <li>Look for surface deterioration</li>
                                        <li>Check for wet or contaminated areas</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="mb-0"><strong>Plan routes that use the best surfaces available.</strong></p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="path-factor-card">
                                <div class="path-factor-header">
                                    <div class="path-factor-number">4</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Turning Space Availability</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="path-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Ensure adequate space to make turns safely:</p>
                                    <ul class="mb-3">
                                        <li>Can you complete turns without reversing?</li>
                                        <li>Is there room to turn with the load?</li>
                                        <li>Check turning radius requirements for your specific forklift model</li>
                                        <li>Consider rear-end swing when turning</li>
                                        <li>Identify areas where three-point turns may be needed</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="mb-0"><strong>Tight corners require extra caution and may require you to slow down significantly or find an alternative route.</strong></p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="path-factor-card">
                                <div class="path-factor-header">
                                    <div class="path-factor-number">5</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Visibility Along the Path</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="path-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Assess how well you'll be able to see while traveling:</p>
                                    <ul class="mb-3">
                                        <li>Blind corners or intersections</li>
                                        <li>Areas with limited lighting</li>
                                        <li>Locations where the load may block your view</li>
                                        <li>Availability of mirrors or other visibility aids</li>
                                        <li>Whether you'll need a spotter in certain areas</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="path-tip-box">
                                        <strong>If your view will be obstructed, plan to:</strong>
                                        <ul class="mb-0">
                                            <li>Travel in reverse</li>
                                            <li>Use a spotter</li>
                                            <li>Proceed at reduced speed</li>
                                            <li>Sound your horn at intersections</li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="path-factor-card">
                                <div class="path-factor-header">
                                    <div class="path-factor-number">6</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Pedestrian Crossing Points</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="path-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Identify where pedestrians may cross or enter your travel path:</p>
                                    <ul class="mb-3">
                                        <li>Designated pedestrian crossings</li>
                                        <li>Doorways where people enter/exit buildings</li>
                                        <li>Break room or office entrances</li>
                                        <li>Amenities access points (toilets, etc.)</li>
                                        <li>Areas with high foot traffic</li>
                                        <li>Times when pedestrian traffic increases (shift changes, lunch breaks)</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="mb-0"><strong>Plan to slow down or stop at these points.</strong></p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="path-factor-card">
                                <div class="path-factor-header">
                                    <div class="path-factor-number">7</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Loading and Unloading Area Suitability</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="path-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Check that destination areas are appropriate:</p>
                                    <ul class="mb-3">
                                        <li>Adequate space to maneuver the forklift</li>
                                        <li>Room to position loads accurately</li>
                                        <li>Surface suitable for loaded operations</li>
                                        <li>Area clear of other materials or obstructions</li>
                                        <li>Properly lit and ventilated</li>
                                        <li>Racking or storage systems accessible</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="mb-0"><strong>If the destination area isn't suitable, report this before beginning work.</strong></p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="path-factor-card">
                                <div class="path-factor-header">
                                    <div class="path-factor-number">8</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Proximity to Hazards</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="path-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Identify hazards near your travel path:</p>
                                    <ul class="mb-3">
                                        <li>Overhead power lines</li>
                                        <li>Underground services (marked or unmarked)</li>
                                        <li>Emergency equipment (fire extinguishers, hoses, first aid)</li>
                                        <li>Fragile or valuable stored goods</li>
                                        <li>Pinch points between structures</li>
                                        <li>Drop-offs or edges (loading docks, platforms)</li>
                                        <li>Work being performed by others (maintenance, construction)</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="mb-0"><strong>Maintain safe distances from all hazards.</strong></p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="path-factor-card">
                                <div class="path-factor-header">
                                    <div class="path-factor-number">9</div>
                                    <h5 class="mb-0">Traffic Flow Patterns</h5>
                                </div>
                                <div class="path-factor-body">
                                    <p class="mb-2">Understand traffic management in the area:</p>
                                    <ul class="mb-3">
                                        <li>One-way traffic systems</li>
                                        <li>Intersections or merging areas</li>
                                        <li>Peak traffic times</li>
                                        <li>Other forklifts or vehicles operating</li>
                                        <li>Delivery truck access routes</li>
                                        <li>Designated forklift-only areas vs. mixed traffic areas</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <p class="mb-0"><strong>Coordinate your movements with other operators.</strong></p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
